Using Git and GitHub for version control and reproducible data analysis

Jocelyn Mara PhD, University of Canberra

Activity Overview

In this activity you will create a reproducible project to analyse rugby data. This activity will provide you with the opportunity to practice the following:

  1. Creating a repository on GitHub1 to host a data analysis project
  2. Cloning your GitHub repository to a local directory on your computer
  3. Making changes to your project locally on your computer (e.g. creating new directories, adding analysis and data files etc)
  4. Conducting exploratory analysis using an RStudio Project
  5. Adding, committing and pushing these changes using Git2 to your remote repository on GitHub.

The Data

The data we will use for this activity is stored in the 2017_super-rugby_try-source-data.csv file. This data consists of tries that were scored during the 2017 Super Rugby competition (observations/rows). Here is a description of the variables:

  1. try_no: a unique identification number given to each try
  2. round_no: an identification number to distinguish the round number the try was scored in
  3. attacking_team: the try-scoring team
  4. defending_team: the opposition team who conceded the try
  5. attacking_rank: the final league ranking at the end of the season of the try-scoring team
  6. defending_rank: the final league ranking at the end of the season of the opposition team
  7. attacking_conference: the conference group of the try-scoring team
  8. defending_conference: the conference group of the opposition team
  9. game_time: the game time in minutes when the try was scored
  10. try_source: the initial source of possession for the attacking team preceding the try
  11. final_source: the event that directly preceded the try and resulted in the try being scored
  12. phases: the total number of phases between gaining possession, and the try being scored (a phase is from one ruck to the next ruck)
  13. time_from_source: the time taken from gaining possession to scoring the try, in seconds
  14. possession_zone: the zone on the field the attacking team gained possession of the ball before scoring the try (A = attacking 22m line to try-line, B = halfway to attacking 22m line, C = defensive 22m line to halfway, D = )
  15. offloads: the number of offloads from gaining possession to the try being scored
  16. passes: the number of passes from gaining possession to the try being scored
  17. total_passes: the number of offloads plus passes

This data was collected by a former UC student, Molly Coughlan, as part of a project that identified playing patterns that led to tries in super rugby3

Step 1. Create a new repository on GitHub to store your data analysis project in.

Give it a meaningful name following best-practice for naming directories. You should also initialise the repository with a README.md file. Notice that the extension of this README file is .md. That means it is a markdown file. This means that all of the markdown language syntax (e.g. headers, code, bolding and italicising, equations etc) you learnt in the R Markdown lesson will apply to this file.

Example solution

Step 2. Clone your GitHub repository to a local directory on your computer.

You might like to create a directory on your computer called repos or something similar to clone your project repository in.

Example solution

Click on “Clone or download” and then copy the link to the repository in the dropdown box:

Then in Git bash (Windows users) or Terminal (Mac users), change the directory to the repos directory, and type the following at the prompt:

This will initiate a local Git repository:

$ git init

This will point the local repository at the GitHub repository (change your GitHub username and repo name accordingly):

$ git remote add origin https://github.com/jocelyn-mara/rugby-try-analysis.git

This will clone the GitHub repository into the local repository (change your GitHub username and repo name accordingly):

$ git clone https://github.com/jocelyn-mara/rugby-try-analysis.git

Step 3. Make some changes to your local repository.

Create a data directory to your local root project repository and store the 2017_super-rugby_try-source-data.csv file in it.

Try adding, committing and pushing these changes to your GitHub repository and check what happens.

Example solution

In Git bash (Windows users) or Terminal (Mac users), change to be the local root project repository (change to your directory name accordingly):

$ cd rugby-try-analysis

and you can type the following to add the changes:

$ git add -A

The -A will add all new files and updates the tracking on files that were renamed or deleted.

You could check the status using:

$ git status

You could commit the changes and include a message using:

$ git commit -m "added the data directory"

Finally, push the changes to your remote GitHub profile using:

$ git push

Important: At this point, you may be asked to type in your GitHub username and password in bash/Terminal. As you type in your password, it might not look like anything is typing, but it is. Hit enter for these commands to run.

Check that the changes have been made on your GitHub profile:

Step 4. Create a new RStudio Project and initalise it in your existing root project directory.

This will create a new session in RStudio, and save a .Rproj file in your root project directory to ensure you can practice safe relative paths for reproducibility and portability of your project.

Example solution

Go to File > New Project… and create the project using the selection ‘Existing Directory’.

Choose the directory path to your root project directory.

Check that the .Rproj file has been saved in this directory.

Step 5. Add, commit and push these new changes to your remote GitHub repository.

Normally you wouldn’t have to go through this process after every change you make to your local repository, and you would usually do it after every few changes or so. However, repetition is the best practice to help you retain this process in your memory.

Go through the steps of adding, committing and pushing the changes to your remote GitHub repository. Check those changes worked on your GitHub account.

Example solution

In Git bash (Windows users) or Terminal (Mac users), you can type the following to add the changes:

$ git add -A

The -A will add all new files and updates the tracking on files that were renamed or deleted.

You could check the status using:

$ git status

You could commit the changes and include a message using:

$ git commit -m "created a new RStudio Project file"

Push the changes to your remote GitHub profile using:

$ git push

Check that the .Rproj was pushed to the GitHub repo:

Note: there was a hidden directory .Rproj.user that was also pushed to my GitHub repo during this process.

To avoid pushing hidden directories/files like this, you can just use $ git add filename to specify individual files to add, commit and push.

Step 6. Create a new R Markdown document and/or R script files for your analysis.

Create an R Markdown document to store your R code, output and descriptions etc so you can practice literate programming. You could also generate a html report from this R Markdown document if you would like. Think about where the best place to store this R Markdown document would be.

In addition, you might also like to create any .R script files if there are particular functions or longer sequences of code you will need to source. The necessity of this option might become clearer as you move through the analysis.

To keep up with the Git practice, add, commit and push these new additions to your GitHub repository.

Step 7. Analyse the rugby data.

This step has quite a few “sub-steps” to follow and you can complete them by writing code in your R Markdown document. Make sure you follow good practice for writing in code chunks, and practice literate programming by providing good descriptions of what the code is doing.

  1. Read the 2017_super-rugby_try-source-data.csv file into RStudio and take a look at its structure.

  2. Are there any missing values in the data set? Where are they?

  3. The missing values in this data actually represent 0’s. For example, if there were no passes for a try, that was left blank. Replace the missing values with 0’s.

  4. Create exploratory graphs to visualise the univariate distribution (i.e. variation in single variables) for the following variables: attacking_team, game_time, try_source, final_source, possession_zone, time_from_source and any other variables you might be interested in. Interpret and describe what each graph is telling you about the try-scoring patterns. Play around with the fill and border colours for each graph as well.

  5. Create exploratory graphs to visualise the covariation between two or more variables at once. You can choose which variables you would like to explore. What try-scoring patterns can you identify?

  6. Conduct any other exploratory analysis you would like. e.g. you might like to provide some summary/descriptive statistics on the continuous variables to practice using the group_by() and summarise() functions from the dplyr package.

  7. Finally, knit your R Markdown document to a HTML and/or PDF document.

Step 8. Add, commit and push your new changes to your remote GitHub repository.

Double check that the changes to your .Rmd file have been uploaded to your GitHub repo, as well as the new .html and/or .pdf documents.

Take a look at how the .Rmd file looks when you open it from GitHub.

Example

Also note the way your .html file looks when you open it in GitHub. You will notice that it is presented as the “raw” html language, rather than as the pretty “marked-up” .html document that is in your local repo.

Example

This is because GitHub renders .md (markdown) files, but not .html files. Don’t worry too much about this for now, I will show you how to deal with this during the week 11 lessons when we talk about creating graphics for communication. The important thing is, if someone was to clone your GitHub repository to their computer, the .html document will open as the pretty “marked-up” document when they view it locally on their computer.

Also note that if you host a .pdf file in your remote GitHub repo, this will appear as normal when you open it in GitHub.

Step 9. Make some changes to your README.md file on GitHub.

It is important to provide a descriptive README.md file on GitHub to explain what the aim of repository is, and describe the contents of the repository.

Edit the README.md file on GitHub and provide a description of your repo. Remember that this file will use the markdown language, so play around with headings, styling (bold and italics), bullet points, ordered lists etc.

Step 10. Pull your remote changes to your local repository.

You now need to pull the changes you just made remotely on GitHub to your local repository on the computer.

Example solution

In Git bash (Windows users) or Terminal (Mac users), you could use the following to pull changes (change to your repo name accordingly):

$ git pull https://github.com/jocelyn-mara/rugby-try-analysis.git master

Summary

Well done on completing this activity on version control using Git and GitHub! You should now be familiar with creating a new repository on GitHub, adding, committing and pushing local changes to your remote repository, and pulling changes from your remote repository to your local repository.
